"about 1310":"about 1310","about 1340":"about 1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wilford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from either of two places called Wilford, in Nottinghamshire and Suffolk, both probably named with an Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow tree’ + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Americanized form of German   Wilfert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wilfert","meanings":["German:","from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wolf</i> ‘wolf’ + <i>hart</i> ‘hardy, brave’, ‘strong’.","from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>willio</i> ‘will, wish’ + <i>fridu</i> ‘peace’."]},{"name":"Willford","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, Rutland, and Northamptonshire): variant of   Wilford  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desper